<font color="#FF0000">CHILDREN OF LIVING VN VETERANS</font><br>
<tt>Fri Sep 19 13:59:08 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I am a student, a writer, and also the daughter of a Vietnam Veteran.  My father's experiences as a Marine in Vietnam have had an enormous influence over my own life.  I really believe that my father's inability to make peace with the issues he is still carrying around with him are at the root of the dysfunction of my family.  I have been actively researching the influence of a veteran parent on children for the past two years.  I cannot find anything of real substance; the material is outdated, or only peripheral in self-help type books for wives of PTSD sufferers.  The problem is that my father won't talk about his experience; he knows about the work I do (and has read some of it), but there is a certain awkwardness between us in discussing it.  I have great empathy for the children of the Vietnam era whose fathers were claimed by the war, and for Vietnamese-American children who suffer from a painful sort of liminality induced by the war, but I think that the experiences of children with Veteran parents need to be explored.  I am specifically interested in the transmission of &quot;war stories&quot; from the Vet parent to the child--in my experience, the dark and disturbing one-liners (ie. &quot;I should have been dead already...&quot;) were ever-present, but the &quot;real&quot; stories still remain withheld from me by my father.  I don't want to cause him pain in exploring these issues, but I think it is integral for the transmission of the &quot;real&quot; stories of war to be passed from parent to child in order to ensure that another war like Vietnam will not occur.  It is wrong to allow the education of a generation on Vietnam to come about by sources such as movies or the obligatory half-page allusion in a grade eight history text book.  I am interested in hearing from other children of veterans---how the war (and its emotional fallout) has effected you even in what seems the most remote ways (ie. I have never eaten rice before; my father felt he had eaten enough of it for a lifetime, and did not want it in his house).  Also, I would like to know how other COVs approach the topic in their own homes, and how their Vet parent responded.  Even with all the negatives, there is a positive situation here, one of healing that starts in the family.
<p><code>-- jcolella@wam.umd.edu  (J.M. Colella) </code><p>


